<details class="govuk-details details--chevron-style" data-test-id="details-wrapper-direct-contact-sexual-reoffending-predictor" id="details-direct-contact-sexual-reoffending-predictor">
  <summary class="govuk-details__summary" id="details-summary-direct-contact-sexual-reoffending-predictor" data-test-id="details-summary">
    <span class="details__chevron" aria-hidden="true" data-test-id="details-chevron"></span>
    <span class="details__toggle-text" data-test-id="details-toggle-text">
      <span class="details__show" data-test-id="details-show">
        Show details
        
          <span class="govuk-visually-hidden" data-test-id="details-show-hidden-text"> for the Direct contact sexual reoffending predictor</span>
        
      </span>
      <span class="details__hide" data-test-id="details-hide">
        Hide details
        
          <span class="govuk-visually-hidden" data-test-id="details-hide-hidden-text"> for the Direct contact sexual reoffending predictor</span>
        
      </span>
    </span>
  </summary>
  <section class="govuk-details__text"
           aria-labelledby="details-summary-direct-contact-sexual-reoffending-predictor"
           role="region"
           data-test-id="details-section">
    
            <h3>What this score predicts</h3>
            <p>
              The Direct contact – sexual reoffending predictor predicts the risk of the following offences with an adult victim:
            </p>
            <ul>
              <li>rape or attempted rape</li>
              <li>sexual assault</li>
              <li>causing a female to engage in sexual activity without consent</li>
              <li>sex with an adult relative</li>
              <li>sexual activity with someone with a mental disorder or learning disability, including ‘breach of trust’
                offences
              </li>
              <li>abduction (under the Sexual Offences 1956 Act)</li>
              <li>trafficking for sexual exploitation</li>
              <li>administering a substance with intent to engage in a sexual activity</li>
            </ul>
            <p>It also predicts the risk of the following offences with a child victim:</p>
            <ul>
              <li>rape or attempted rape</li>
              <li>assault by penetration</li>
              <li>sexual assault</li>
              <li>causing a female to engage in sexual activity without consent</li>
              <li>sexual activity with a child family member</li>
              <li>inciting a child family member to engage in sexual activity</li>
              <li>abuse of trust sexual offences</li>
              <li>abduction (under the Sexual Offences 1956 Act, not the Child Abduction Act 1984)</li>
            </ul>
            <p>
              It does not predict other sexual offences that do not involve actual or attempted physical contact with a live
              human victim. For example:
            </p>
            <ul>
              <li>possession of extreme pornographic images</li>
              <li>exposure</li>
              <li>voyeurism</li>
              <li>sending a photograph or film of genitals</li>
              <li>sharing or threatening to share an intimate photograph or film</li>
            </ul>
            <p>
              Further guidance about the offences it does not predict is available as an annex to the
              <a href="https://equip-portal.equip.service.justice.gov.uk/CtrlWebIsapi.dll/app/documents/091B36B5CE134AC5B45D06A30D09F8B9/master">
                Understanding risk predictors - actuarial risk assessment instruments (ARAI) user guidance (EQUip)
              </a>.
            </p>
            <h3>How we calculate the score</h3>
            <p>
              We only calculate a Direct contact – sexual reoffending predictor score for men with a known history of sexual
              or sexually motivated offending.
            </p>
            <p>We calculate the score using the number of current and previous sanctions a person has for:</p>
            <ul>
              <li>sexual or sexually motivated offences involving contact with an adult</li>
              <li>sexual or sexually motivated offences involving direct contact with a child</li>
              <li>non-contact sexual offences</li>
            </ul>
            <p>It does not count indecent images of children offences.</p>
            <p>We also look at static factors, which are things which cannot be deliberately changed. These include:</p>
            <ul>
              <li>age when they enter the community caseload</li>
              <li>total number of sanctions</li>
              <li>if their current offence was a direct contact offence committed against a stranger victim</li>
            </ul>
          
  </section>
</details>

          </div>
        
      
    </section>

    
    <section role="region" aria-labelledby="iicsrp-heading">
      <div class="predictor-header-wrapper">
